\begin_layout Subsubsection
Order of convergence of a sequence
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
convergence ! order of
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 converges with order 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq1$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n}-p\right|^{\alpha}}=\lambda
\]

\end_inset

for some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's see how to use this definition to calculate the orders of convergence
 of the sequences in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:convergenceTo2.718281828..."

\end_inset

.
 According to the definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, should it exist, gives the speed (or order) of convergence 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
convergence ! order of
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of a sequence.
 Now assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 does exist, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n}-p\right|^{\alpha}}=\lambda$
\end_inset

, so for large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n}-p\right|^{\alpha}}\approx\frac{\left|p_{n+2}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|^{\alpha}}\approx\lambda.
\]

\end_inset

In particular, we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to find 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \alpha\approx\frac{\ln\left|\frac{p_{n+2}-p}{p_{n+1}-p}\right|}{\ln\left|\frac{p_{n+1}-p}{p_{n}-p}\right|}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{digression}{Order of Convergence Less than or equal to 1?} 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
There is no such thing as an order of convergence 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
convergence ! order of
\end_layout

\end_inset

 less than one because if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n}-p\right|^{\alpha}}=\lambda$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{|p_{n+1}-p|}{|p_{n}-p|} & = & \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{|p_{n+1}-p|}{|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha}}\cdot|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha-1},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

a contradiction.
 On the one hand, the ratio test implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{|p_{n+1}-p|}{|p_{n}-p|}$
\end_inset

 exists and is less than or equal to 1.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<1\implies\alpha-1<0$
\end_inset

 so for 
\begin_inset Formula $|p_{n}-p|$
\end_inset

 small, 
\begin_inset Formula $|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha-1}$
\end_inset

 is large.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{|p_{n+1}-p|}{|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha}}\cdot|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha-1}$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
 To be rigorous, let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be any real number.
 Then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n>N_{1}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{|p_{n+1}-p|}{|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha}}>0.9\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 There also exists 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n>N_{2}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle |p_{n}-p|<\left(\frac{0.9\lambda}{M}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\alpha}}}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha-1}>\frac{M}{0.9\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\max\{N_{1},N_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $n>N$
\end_inset

 implies both 
