, but what does it all mean? What does the order of convergence tell us
 about successive terms in the sequence? Solving the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left|p_{n+1}-p\right|}{\left|p_{n}-p\right|^{\alpha}}\approx\lambda$
\end_inset

 gives us that 
\begin_inset Formula $|p_{n+1}-p|\approx\lambda|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 So, roughly speaking, convergence of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 means that, for large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha-1}$
\end_inset

 times closer to the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 than is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To rephrase in terms of significant digits of accuracy, a little bit of
 algebra:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
|p_{n+1}-p| & \approx & \lambda|p_{n}-p|^{\alpha}\\
\left|\frac{p_{n+1}-p}{p}\right| & \approx & \lambda\left|\frac{p_{n}-p}{p}\right|^{\alpha}\cdot|p|^{\alpha-1}\\
-\log\left|\frac{p_{n+1}-p}{p}\right| & \approx & -\log\left|\frac{p_{n}-p}{p}\right|^{\alpha}-\log\left(\lambda|p|^{\alpha-1}\right)\\
d(p_{n+1}) & \approx & \alpha d(p_{n})-\log\left(\lambda|p|^{\alpha-1}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Based on this calculation, we conclude these rules of thumb:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for linear convergence (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $d(p_{n+1})\approx d(p_{n})-\log\lambda$
\end_inset

, so each term has a fixed number more significant digits of accuracy (approxima
tely equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\log\lambda$
\end_inset

) than the previous;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for quadratic convergence (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=2$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $d(p_{n+1})\approx2d(p_{n})-\log\left(\lambda|p|\right)$
\end_inset

, so each term has double the number of significant digits of accuracy of
 the previous, give or take some;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
for cubic convergence (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=3$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $d(p_{n+1})\approx3d(p_{n})-\log\left(\lambda|p|^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, so each term has triple the number of significant digits of accuracy of
 the previous, give or take some;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and so on.
 Summarizing, for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, you can expect that each term will have 
\begin_inset Formula $-\log\left(\lambda|p|^{\alpha-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 more than 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 times as many significant digits of accuracy as the previous term.
