 In particular, a first order linear nonhomogeneous recurrence relation
 with constant coefficients since it has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n+1}=k_{1}a_{n}+k_{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 Linear nonhomogeneous recurrence relations can be solved by summing a homogeneo
us solution and a particular solution.
 For the particular solution, we seek a solution of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=A$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) by substituting this assumed solution into the recurrence relation.
 Doing so gives 
\begin_inset Formula $A=k_{1}A+k_{2}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\frac{k_{2}}{1-k_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is such a solution.
 For the homogeneous solution, we seek a sequence of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=r^{n}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}=k_{1}a_{n}+0$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting our assumed solution into the modified (homogeneous) recurrence
 relation gives 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{n+1}=k_{1}r^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Rearranging, 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{n}(r-k_{1})=0$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r=k_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $Bk_{1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is also a solution for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 This includes the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 which would arise from setting 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
